# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bangor-maine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bangor-maine/101st-air-refueling-wing] The **101st Air Refueling Wing (101 ARW)** is a unit of the Maine Air National Guard, stationed at Bangor Air National Guard Base, Bangor, Maine.
[src:bangor-maine/101st-air-refueling-wing] If activated to federal service with the United States Air Force, the 101 ARW is operationally-gained by the Air Mobility Command (AMC).
[src:bangor-maine/101st-air-refueling-wing] The mission of the 101st FIW was the air defense of New England.
[src:bangor-maine/1800-united-states-census] The **1800 United States census** was the second census conducted in the United States.
[src:bangor-maine/1800-united-states-census] It showed that 5,308,483 people were living in the United States, of whom 893,602 were slaves.
[src:bangor-maine/1800-united-states-census] The 1800 census included the new District of Columbia.
[src:bangor-maine/1800-united-states-census] The census for the following states were lost: Georgia, Kentucky, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:bangor-maine/1800-united-states-census] In comparison to the 1790 census, the 1800 census gathered additional information.
[src:bangor-maine/1800-united-states-census] The census was published in December 1801 and cost $66,109.04.
[src:bangor-maine/1800-united-states-census] This census is one of the several for which some of the original data are no longer available.
[src:bangor-maine/1800-united-states-census] Original census returns for Georgia, Kentucky, Mississippi, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia were lost over the years.
[src:bangor-maine/1800-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1800 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:bangor-maine/1810-united-states-census] The **1810 United States census** was the third census conducted in the United States.
[src:bangor-maine/1810-united-states-census] It showed that 7,239,881 people were living in the United States, of whom 1,191,362 were slaves.
[src:bangor-maine/1810-united-states-census] The 1810 census included one new state: Ohio.
[src:bangor-maine/1810-united-states-census] The original census returns for the District of Columbia, Georgia, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Ohio were lost or destroyed over the years.
[src:bangor-maine/1810-united-states-census] Most of Tennessee's original forms were also lost, other than Grainger and Rutherford counties.
[src:bangor-maine/1810-united-states-census] This was the last census with Virginia ranked as the most populous state.
[src:bangor-maine/1810-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:bangor-maine/1810-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and some drew up their own, resulting in pages without headings.
[src:bangor-maine/1810-united-states-census] Some enumerators did not tally their results.
[src:bangor-maine/1810-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:bangor-maine/1810-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:bangor-maine/1810-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1810 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:bangor-maine/1820-united-states-census] The **1820 United States census** was the fourth census conducted in the United States.
[src:bangor-maine/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census included six new states: Louisiana, Indiana, Mississippi, Illinois, Alabama and Maine.
[src:bangor-maine/1820-united-states-census] There has been a district wide loss of 1820 census records for Arkansas Territory, Missouri Territory, and New Jersey.
[src:bangor-maine/1820-united-states-census] The total population was determined to be 9,638,453, of which 1,538,022 were slaves.
[src:bangor-maine/1820-united-states-census] The center of population was about 120 miles (193 km) west-northwest of Washington in Hardy County, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:bangor-maine/1820-united-states-census] This was the first census in which any states recorded a population of over one million—New York, Virginia, and Pennsylvania—as well as the first in which a city recorded a population of over 100,000—New York.
[src:bangor-maine/1820-united-states-census] Also, in this census and the 14 subsequent ones, New York was the most populous state until being superseded by California in the 1970 census.
[src:bangor-maine/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census contains a great deal more information than previous censuses.
[src:bangor-maine/1820-united-states-census] Several of these columns were for special counts, and not to be included in the aggregate total.
[src:bangor-maine/1820-united-states-census] Doing so would have resulted in counting some individuals twice.
[src:bangor-maine/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were asked to use double lines, red ink or some other method of distinguishing these columns so that double counting would not occur.
[src:bangor-maine/1820-united-states-census] For example, the count of free white males between 16 and 18 was a special count, because these individuals were also supposed to be tabulated in the column for free white males of age 16 and under 26.
[src:bangor-maine/1820-united-states-census] The other special counts were foreigners not naturalized, persons engaged in agriculture, persons engaged in commerce, and persons engaged in manufacture.
[src:bangor-maine/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were also instructed to count each individual in only one of the occupational columns.
[src:bangor-maine/1820-united-states-census] For example, if an individual was engaged in agriculture, commerce, and manufacture, the census taker had to judge which one the individual was primarily engaged in.
[src:bangor-maine/1820-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and drew up their own, sometimes resulting in pages without headings, line tallies, or column totals.
[src:bangor-maine/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:bangor-maine/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:bangor-maine/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:bangor-maine/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:bangor-maine/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:bangor-maine/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:bangor-maine/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:bangor-maine/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:bangor-maine/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:bangor-maine/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:bangor-maine/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:bangor-maine/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:bangor-maine/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:bangor-maine/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:bangor-maine/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:bangor-maine/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:bangor-maine/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:bangor-maine/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:bangor-maine/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:bangor-maine/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:bangor-maine/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Modern Bangor was established in the mid-19th century with the lumber and shipbuilding industries.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Due to the city's location on the Penobscot River, logs could be floated downstream from the Maine North Woods and processed at the city's water-powered sawmills, then shipped from Bangor's port to the Atlantic Ocean 30 miles (48 km) downstream, and from there to any port in the world.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Evidence of this is still visible in the lumber barons' elaborate Greek Revival and Victorian mansions and the 31-foot-high (9.4 m) statue of Paul Bunyan.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Today, Bangor's economy is based on services and retail, healthcare, and education.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor has a port of entry at Bangor International Airport, also home to the Bangor Air National Guard Base.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Historically Bangor was an important stopover on the Great Circle Air Route between the U.S.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Founded as Kenduskeag Plantation in 1791, Bangor was incorporated as a town in 1834.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The name Bangor is said to have been taken from a Welsh hymn tune.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] It is also the name of the city of Bangor, Gwynedd ("bangor" in Old Welsh means "wattled enclosure").
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In 2015, local celebrities and business owners recorded the YouTube video "How to Say Bangor", which was sung to the tune of "We Are the World".
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The Penobscot people have inhabited the area around present-day Bangor for at least 11,000 years and continue to occupy tribal land on the nearby Penobscot Indian Island Reservation.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The Penobscot traditionally call the Bangor area *kkάtaskkik*, meaning "at/on the water parsnip ground," which European colonists rendered in English as Kenduskeag.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The Penobscot practiced some agriculture but relied more heavily on hunting and gathering than indigenous peoples in warmer southern New England.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Contact with Europeans began in the 16th century through the lucrative fur trade, as the Penobscot traded pelts for European goods.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The first documented European exploration of the area was conducted by Estêvão Gomes, a Portuguese navigator in Spanish service, in 1524.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The Jesuits established a mission on Penobscot Bay in 1609 as part of the French colony of Acadia.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The Penobscot River valley remained contested between France and Britain until the 1750s.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] European settlement began in 1769 when Jacob Buswell established a community at the future site of Bangor.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] By 1772, twelve families lived in the settlement alongside a sawmill, store, and school.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Initially known as Sunbury or Kenduskeag Plantation, the community was incorporated as Bangor in 1791.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The name "Bangor" is the Welsh word for wattled enclosure.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] It shares the name of Bangor, Gwynedd, the oldest city in Wales as well as Bangor, County Down in Northern Ireland.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In the Irish language, Bangor is an anglicisation of *Beannchar*, meaning 'horned curve' referring to the shoreline of a bay.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] During the American Revolutionary War, Bangor played a role in the Penobscot Expedition of 1779.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] When the expedition failed, ten American naval vessels fled up the Penobscot River and were scuttled near Bangor to prevent capture by British forces.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The ship remains lay undisturbed until construction of the Joshua Chamberlain Bridge in the late 1950s exposed the archaeological site.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Six cannons were recovered from the riverbed; five remain on display in the region.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] During the War of 1812, British forces under Robert Barrie briefly occupied Bangor in 1814 following the Battle of Hampden.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Maine remained part of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts until 1820, when it was admitted to the Union as the 23rd state under the Missouri Compromise.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The mid-19th century marked Bangor's emergence as a major lumber center.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The Penobscot River drainage basin proved ideal for the timber industry despite being unsuitable for agriculture.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Winter snow allowed horse teams to drag logs from forests to the Penobscot River and its tributaries.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Log driving during spring snowmelt transported timber to water-powered sawmills upriver from Bangor.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The processed lumber was then shipped from Bangor's port to markets worldwide.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor's strategic location at the head of navigation on the Penobscot River—where rapids met tidal waters—made it an ideal shipping point.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Local capitalists owned much of the region's forestland, and Bangor-built ships carried lumber to East Coast cities, the Caribbean, and California during the California Gold Rush.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The lumber trade established connections that led to the founding of communities named Bangor in Washington, California, and Nevada.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] By 1860, Bangor had become the world's largest lumber port.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The city operated 150 sawmills along the river and shipped over 150 million board feet of lumber annually.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In 1860 alone, 3,300 lumber ships passed through Bangor's docks.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The prosperity of the lumber trade enabled the construction of elaborate Greek Revival and Victorian mansions, many of which survive in the Broadway Historic District.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The Aroostook War of 1838–1839, a boundary dispute between the United States and Britain, highlighted the growing importance of Maine's lumber industry.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor emerged as both a lumbering boomtown and a potential rival to Portland's political dominance in the state.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The American Civil War significantly impacted Bangor.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In 1861, a mob attacked the offices of the *Bangor Daily Union*, a Democratic newspaper whose editor Marcellus Emery held Southern sympathies.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The attackers destroyed the presses and burned equipment in the street, forcing the paper to suspend publication until after the war.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor contributed substantially to the Union war effort.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The locally recruited 2nd Maine Volunteer Infantry Regiment was among the first units to leave Maine in 1861 and participated in the First Battle of Bull Run.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The 1st Maine Heavy Artillery Regiment, also mustered in Bangor, suffered the highest casualties of any Union regiment during the war, particularly at the Second Battle of Petersburg in 1864.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The 20th Maine Infantry Regiment achieved fame for its defense of Little Round Top during the Battle of Gettysburg under Joshua Chamberlain, for whom a local bridge is named.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Boutelle accepted the surrender of Confederate naval forces after the Battle of Mobile Bay.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Beyond lumber, 19th-century Bangor developed diverse manufacturing capabilities.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The city became a leading producer of moccasins, shipping over 100,000 pairs annually by the 1880s.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Other exports included bricks, leather, and ice, which was harvested in winter and shipped to markets as distant as China, the West Indies, and South America.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Despite its success, Bangor faced geographic limitations.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] As a northern river port, it froze during winter months and could not accommodate the largest ocean-going vessels.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The sparse settlement of its forested hinterland also limited the local market compared to competitors like Portland, Maine.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In 1844, the first ocean-going iron-hulled steamship in the United States was named *The Bangor*.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Built by Harlan and Hollingsworth in Wilmington, Delaware, the vessel was designed for passenger service between Bangor and Boston.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] However, on its second voyage in 1845, the ship burned near Castine.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Though rebuilt in Bath, it was soon sold to the U.S. government for service in the Mexican–American War.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Local industry innovation continued into the early 20th century.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor's Hinkley & Egery Ironworks (later Union Ironworks) developed a steam engine called the "Endeavor" that won a gold medal at the New York Crystal Palace Exhibition in 1856.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Sargent invented the first automotive snow plow in the 1920s, which the company manufactured for national distribution.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The late 19th and early 20th centuries saw Bangor's economy transition as the pulp and paper industry replaced traditional lumbering, and railroads superseded river transportation for moving goods.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Local investors supported railroad development, including the Bangor and Aroostook Railroad, which opened northern Aroostook County to settlement and economic development.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Major fires periodically disrupted the city's development, with significant blazes in 1856, 1869, and 1872.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The Great Fire of 1911 proved most devastating, destroying Bangor's high school, post office, public library, telephone and telegraph companies, banks, two fire stations, nearly 100 businesses, six churches, a synagogue, and 285 private residences across 55 acres.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The subsequent rebuilding created an architectural showcase featuring diverse styles including Mansard, Beaux-Arts, Greek Revival, and Colonial Revival, now preserved as the Great Fire of 1911 Historic District.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 34.59 square miles (89.59 km2), of which 34.26 square miles (88.73 km2) is land and 0.33 square miles (0.85 km2) is water.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] A potential advantage that has always eluded exploitation is the city's location between the port city of Halifax, Nova Scotia, and the rest of Canada (as well as New York).
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] As early as the 1870s, the city promoted a Halifax-to-New York railroad, via Bangor, as the quickest connection between North America and Europe (when combined with steamship service between Britain and Halifax).
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] A European and North American Railway opened through Bangor, with President Ulysses S.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Grant officiating at the inauguration, but commerce never lived up to the potential.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] More recent attempts to capture traffic between Halifax and Montreal by constructing an East–West Highway through Maine have also come to naught.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Most overland traffic between the two parts of Canada continues to travel north of Maine rather than across it.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Major fires struck the downtown in 1856, 1869, and 1872, the last resulting in the erection of the Adams-Pickering Block.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The destruction of downtown landmarks such as the old city hall and train station in the late 1960s urban renewal program is now considered to have been a mistake.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] It ushered in a decline of the city center that was accelerated by the construction of the Bangor Mall in 1978 and subsequent big-box stores on the city's outskirts.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Downtown Bangor began to recover in the 1990s, with bookstores, café/restaurants, galleries, and museums filling once-vacant storefronts.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The recent re-development of the city's waterfront has also helped re-focus cultural life in the historic center.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor is on the banks of the Penobscot River, close enough to the Atlantic Ocean to be influenced by tides.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Upstream, the Penobscot River drainage basin occupies 8,570 square miles (22,200 km2) in northeastern Maine.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Flooding is most often caused by a combination of precipitation and snowmelt.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Ice jams can exacerbate high flow conditions and cause acute localized flooding.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Conditions favorable for flooding typically occur during the spring months.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In 1807 an ice jam formed below Bangor Village, raising the water 10 to 12 feet (3 to 3.7 m) above the normal highwater mark and in 1887 the freshet caused the Maine Central Railroad Company rails between Bangor and Vanceboro to be covered to a depth of several feet.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor's worst ice-jam floods occurred in 1846 and 1902.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Both resulted from mid-December freshets that cleared the upper river of ice, followed by cold that produced large volumes of frazil ice or slush which was carried by high flows, forming a major ice jam in the lower river.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In March of both years, a dynamic breakup of ice ran into the jam and flooded downtown Bangor.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Though no people died and the city recovered quickly, the 1846 and 1902 ice-jam floods were economically devastating, according to the Army Corps analysis.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Both floods occurred with multiple dams in place and little to no ice-breaking in the lower river.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The United States Coast Guard began icebreaker operations on the Penobscot in the 1940s, preventing the formation of frozen ice jams during the winter and providing an unobstructed path for ice-out in the spring.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Long-term temperature records show a gradual warming since 1894, which may have reduced the ice-jam flood potential at Bangor.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In the Groundhog Day gale of 1976, a storm surge went up the Penobscot, flooding Bangor for three hours.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] At 11:15 am, waters began rising on the river and within 15 minutes had risen a total of 12 feet (3.7 m), flooding downtown.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] About 200 cars were submerged and office workers were stranded until waters receded.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] There were no reported deaths during this unusual flash flood.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor has a humid continental climate (Köppen: *Dfb*), with cold, snowy winters, and warm summers, and is in USDA hardiness zone 5a.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The monthly daily average temperature ranges from 18.5 °F (−7.5 °C) in January to 69.5 °F (20.8 °C) in July.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] On average, there are 20 nights annually that drop to 0 °F (−18 °C) or below, and 55 days where the temperature stays below freezing, including 49 days from December through February.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] There is an average of 6.1 days annually with highs at or above 90 °F (32 °C), with the 2014 the last year not to have seen such high temperatures.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The average first freeze of the season occurs on October 7, and the last May 7, resulting in a freeze-free season of 152 days; the corresponding dates for measurable snowfall, i.e. at least 0.1 in (0.25 cm), are November 23 and April 4.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] A snow depth of at least 3 in (7.6 cm) is on average seen 66 days per winter, including 54 days from January to March, when the snow pack is typically most reliable.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] As of 2008, Bangor is the third most populous city in Maine, as it has been for more than a century.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] As of 2012, the estimated population of the Bangor Metropolitan Area (which includes Penobscot County) is 153,746, indicating a slight growth rate since 2000, almost all of it accounted for by Bangor.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Historically Bangor received many immigrants as it industrialized.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Irish-Catholic and later Jewish immigrants eventually became established members of the community, along with many migrants from Atlantic Canada.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Of the 205 Black citizens who lived in Bangor in 1910, over a third were originally from Canada.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] As of the 2020 census, Bangor had a population of 31,753.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The population density was 926.9 inhabitants per square mile (357.9/km2).
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] 16.7% of residents were under the age of 18 and 19.1% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] For every 100 females there were 93.1 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 91.1 males age 18 and over.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] 92.4% of residents lived in urban areas, while 7.6% lived in rural areas.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] There were 14,607 households in Bangor, of which 20.9% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Of all households, 31.0% were married-couple households, 24.0% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 34.9% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] About 40.5% of all households were made up of individuals and 14.4% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] There were 15,900 housing units, of which 8.1% were vacant.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The housing unit density was 464.1 per square mile (179.2/km2).
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.6% and the rental vacancy rate was 6.3%.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] As of the census of 2010, there were 33,039 people, 14,475 households, and 7,182 families residing in the city.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The population density was 964.4 inhabitants per square mile (372.4/km2).
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] There were 15,674 housing units at an average density of 457.5 per square mile (176.6/km2).
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The racial makeup of the city was 93.1% White, 1.7% African American, 1.2% Native American, 1.7% Asian, 0.3% from other races, and 2.0% from two or more races.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 1.5% of the population.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] There were 14,475 households, of which 24.2% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 32.8% were married couples living together, 12.6% had a female householder with no husband present, 4.2% had a male householder with no wife present, and 50.4% were non-families.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] 37.9% of all households were made up of individuals, and 12.4% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The average household size was 2.10 and the average family size was 2.76.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The median age in the city was 36.7 years.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] 17.8% of residents were under the age of 18; 16% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 26% were from 25 to 44; 25.8% were from 45 to 64; and 14.4% were 65 years of age or older.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The gender makeup of the city was 48.2% male and 51.8% female.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor is the largest market town, distribution center, transportation hub, and media center in a five-county area whose population tops 330,000 and which includes Penobscot, Piscataquis, Hancock, Aroostook, and Washington counties.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor's city council has approved a resolution opposing the sale of sweat-shop-produced clothing in local stores.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Outdoor activities in the Bangor City Forest and other nearby parks, forests, and waterways include hiking, sailing, canoeing, hunting, fishing, skiing, and snowmobiling.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor Raceway at the Bass Park Civic Center and Auditorium offers live, pari-mutuel harness racing from May through July and then briefly in the fall.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Hollywood Casino, operated by Penn National Gaming, originally opened as a slot machine only facility.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In 2007, construction began on a $131-million casino complex in Bangor that houses, among other things, a gaming floor with about 1,000 slot machines, an off-track betting center, a seven-story hotel, and a four-level parking garage.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In 2011, it was authorized to add table games.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor Air National Guard Base is a United States Air National Guard base.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Created in 1927 as a commercial field, it was taken over by the U.S.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In 1968, the base was sold to the city of Bangor, Maine, to become Bangor International Airport but has since continued to host the 101st Air Refueling Wing, Maine Air National Guard, part of the Northeast Tanker Task Force.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In 1990, the USAF East Coast Radar System (ECRS) Operation Center was activated in Bangor with over 400 personnel.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The center controlled the over-the-horizon radar's transmitter in Moscow, Maine, and receiver in Columbia Falls, Maine.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Many buildings and monuments are listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The city has also had a municipal Historic Preservation Commission since the early 1980s.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor has many Greek Revival, Victorian, and Colonial Revival houses.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The bow-plate of the battleship USS *Maine*, whose destruction in Havana, Cuba, presaged the start of the Spanish–American War, survives on a granite memorial by Charles Eugene Tefft in Davenport Park.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor has a large fiberglass-over-metal statue of mythical lumberman Paul Bunyan by Normand Martin (1959).
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] There are three large bronze statues in downtown Bangor by sculptor Charles Eugene Tefft of Brewer, including the Luther H.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Peirce Memorial, commemorating the Penobscot River Log-Drivers; a statue of Hannibal Hamlin at Kenduskeag Mall; and an image of "Lady Victory" at Norumbega Parkway.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The abstract aluminum sculpture "Continuity of Community" (1969) on the Bangor Waterfront, formerly in West Market Square, is by the Castine sculptor Clark Battle Fitz-Gerald.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Post Office in Bangor contains Yvonne Jacquette's 1980 three-part mural "Autumn Expansion".
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] A 1962 bronze commemorating the 2nd Maine Volunteer Infantry Regiment by Wisconsin sculptor Owen Vernon Shaffer stands at the entrance to Mount Hope Cemetery.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] A memorial has been placed by Bangor City Council and members of the LGBT community along the Kenduskeag Stream honoring the memory of Charlie Howard as the victim of a hate crime.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In 1984 he was beaten and thrown off Bangor's State Street Bridge by three young men in a what would become a high-profile example of violence against LGBT people.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The murder of Charlie Howard inspired the formation of The Maine Lesbian/Gay Political Alliance, which later became EqualityMaine.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In May 2011, vandals spray-painted graffiti and an anti-gay slur on the memorial.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Family and friends cleaned it up and rededicated it.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] From 2002 to 2017, Bangor had been home to Little League International's Senior League World Series.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor was home to two minor league baseball teams affiliated with the 1995–1998 Northeast League: the Bangor Blue Ox (1996–1997) and the Bangor Lumberjacks (2003–2004).
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Even earlier the Bangor Millionaires (1894–1896) played in the New England League.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Vince McMahon promoted his first professional wrestling event in Bangor in 1979.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In 1985, the WWC Universal Heavyweight Championship changed hands for the first time outside of Puerto Rico at an IWCCW show in Bangor.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The Penobscot is a salmon-fishing river; the Penobscot Salmon Club traditionally sent the first fish caught to the President of the United States.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] From 1999 to 2006, low fish stocks resulted in a ban on salmon fishing.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Today, the wild salmon population (and the sport) is slowly recovering.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The Penobscot River Restoration Project is working to help the fish population by removing some dams north of Bangor.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The Kenduskeag Stream Canoe Race, a white-water event which begins just north of Bangor in Kenduskeag, has been held since 1965.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor is the county seat of Penobscot County.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Since 1931, Bangor has had a council–manager form of government.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The nine-member city council is a nonpartisan body, with three city councilors elected to three-year terms each year.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The nine council members elect the chair of the city council, who is referred to informally as the mayor, and plays the role when there is a ceremonial need.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] As of 2025, the council members are Michael Beck, Susan Deane, Carolyn Fish, Rick Fournier, Susan Hawes, Joseph Leonard, Cara Pelletier (chair), Wayne Mallar, and Dan Tremble.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In 2007, Bangor was the first city in the U.S. to ban smoking in vehicles carrying passengers under the age of 18.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In 2012, Bangor's city council passed an order in support of same-sex marriage in Maine.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In 2013, the City of Bangor also signed an amicus brief to the United States Supreme Court calling for the federal Defense of Marriage Act to be struck down.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In the United States House of Representatives, Bangor is included in Maine's 2nd congressional district and is currently represented by Democrat Jared F.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In 2008 Bangor's crime rate was the second-lowest among American metropolitan areas of comparable size.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] As of 2014 Bangor had the third highest rate of property crime in Maine.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The arrival of Irish immigrants from nearby Canada beginning in the 1830s, and their competition with locals for jobs, sparked a deadly sectarian riot in 1833 that lasted for days and had to be put down by militia.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Realizing the need for a police force, the town incorporated as The City of Bangor in 1834.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In the 1800s, sailors and loggers gave the city a reputation for roughness; their stomping grounds were known as the "Devil's Half Acre".
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The same name was also applied, at roughly the same time, to The Devil's Half-Acre, Pennsylvania.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Although Maine was the first "dry" state (i.e. the first to prohibit the sale of alcohol, with the passage of the "Maine law" in 1851), Bangor managed to remain "wet".
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] A look-the-other-way attitude by local police and politicians (sustained by a system of bribery in the form of ritualized fine-payments known as "The Bangor Plan") allowed Bangor to flout the nation's most long-standing state prohibition law.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In 1913, the war of the "drys" (prohibitionists) on "wet" Bangor escalated when the Penobscot County Sheriff was impeached and removed by the Maine Legislature for not enforcing anti-liquor laws.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] His successor was asked to resign by the governor the following year for the same reason, but refused.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] A third sheriff was removed by the governor in 1918, but promptly re-nominated by the Democratic Party.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Prohibitionist Carrie Nation had been forcibly expelled from the Bangor House hotel in 1902 after causing a disturbance.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In October 1937, "public enemy" Al Brady and another member of his "Brady Gang" (Clarence Shaffer) were killed in the bloodiest shootout in Maine's history.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] FBI agents ambushed Brady, Shaffer, and James Dalhover on Bangor's Central Street after they had attempted to purchase a Thompson submachine gun from Dakin's Sporting Goods downtown.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Brady is buried in the public section of Mount Hope Cemetery, on the north side of Mount Hope Avenue.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Until recently, Brady's grave was unmarked.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] A group of schoolchildren erected a wooden marker over his grave in the 1990s, which was replaced by a more permanent stone in 2007.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor School Department operates public schools, including Bangor High School, the only public high school in the municipality.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The Bangor region has a large number of media outlets for an area its size.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The city has an unbroken history of newspaper publishing extending from 1815.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Almost thirty dailies, weeklies, and monthlies had been launched there by the end of the Civil War.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The *Bangor Daily News* was founded in 1889, and is one of the few remaining family-owned newspapers left in the United States.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] *The Maine Edge* is published from Bangor.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor has more than a dozen radio stations and seven television stations, including WLBZ 2 (NBC), WABI 5 (CBS; CW on DT2), WVII 7 (ABC), WBGR-LD 33 (MeTV), and WFVX-LD 22 (Fox/MyNetworkTV).
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Maine Public Broadcasting Network outlet WMEB 12, licensed to nearby Orono, is the area's PBS member station.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Radio stations in the city include WKIT and WZON, owned by Zone Radio Corporation, a company owned by Bangor resident novelist Stephen King.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] WHSN is a non-commercial alternative rock station licensed to Bangor and run and operated by staff and students at the New England School of Communications on the campus of Husson University.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Several other stations in the market are owned by Blueberry Broadcasting and Townsquare Media.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor sits along interstates I-95 and I-395; U.S. highways US 1A, US 2, US Route 2A, US 202; and state routes SR 9, SR 9 Business, SR 15, SR 15 Business, SR 100, and SR 222.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Three major bridges connect the city to neighboring Brewer: Joshua Chamberlain Bridge (carrying US 1A), Penobscot River Bridge (carrying SR 15), and the Veterans Remembrance Bridge (carrying I-395).
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Daily intercity bus service from Bangor proper is provided by two companies.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Concord Coach Lines connects Bangor with Augusta, Portland, several towns in Maine's midcoast region, and Boston, Massachusetts.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Cyr Bus Lines provides daily service to Caribou and several northern Maine towns along I-95 and Route 1.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The area is also served by Greyhound, which operates out of the Park and Ride lot at 360 Odlin Road.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] West's Bus Service provides service between Bangor and Calais.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In 2011, Acadian Lines ended bus service to Saint John, New Brunswick, because of low ticket sales.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The Community Connector system offers public transportation within Bangor and to adjacent towns such as Orono.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] There is also a seasonal (summer) shuttle between Bangor and Bar Harbor.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Freight service is provided by Pan Am Railways and Central Maine and Quebec Railway, the latter being a successor to locally based Bangor and Aroostook Railroad and Montreal, Maine and Atlantic Railway.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Passenger rail service was discontinued by the BAR in 1961.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] For historic Bangor trolley service see Bangor Railway and Electric Company.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor International Airport (IATA: **BGR**, ICAO: **KBGR**) is a joint civil-military public airport 3 miles (4.8 kilometres) west of the city.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor is the last (or first) American airport along the great circle route between the U.S.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] East Coast and Europe, and in the 1970s and '80s it was a refuelling stop, until the development of longer-range jets in the 1990s.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor is home to two large hospitals, the Eastern Maine Medical Center and the Catholic-affiliated St.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In 1832, a cholera epidemic in Saint John, New Brunswick, (part of the Second cholera pandemic) sent as many as eight hundred poor Irish immigrants walking to Bangor.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] This was the beginning of Maine's first substantial Irish-Catholic community.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Competition with Americans for jobs caused a riot and resulting fire in 1833.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In 1849–50, the Second cholera pandemic reached Bangor itself, killing 20–30 within the first week, 112 had died by October 1849.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] A late outbreak of the disease in 1854 killed seventeen others.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The victims in most cases were poor Irish immigrants.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In 1872, a smallpox epidemic closed local schools.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The Spanish flu pandemic of 1918, which was global in scope, struck over a thousand Bangoreans and killed more than a hundred.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] This was the worst 'natural disaster' in the city's history since the cholera epidemic of 1849.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor is mentioned in the songs King of the Road, I've Been Everywhere, How 'Bout Them Cowgirls, and What the Cowgirls Do.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] In 1977, tourist Erwin Kreuz mistook the city for San Francisco.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Marvel Comics villain MODOK is from Bangor, Maine.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Julie "The Cat" Gaffney from The Mighty Ducks film franchise is from Bangor, Maine.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Bangor International Airport is the main set for the TV series *The Langoliers*.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] Stephen King's novels mention Bangor many times, and some of his movie adaptations have been filmed there.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The 1960s television gothic soap opera Dark Shadows has some scenes set in Bangor, which was the nearest city to the mythical Collinsport.
[src:bangor-maine/bangor-maine] The Canadian mockumentary series Trailer Park Boys features Bangor as the location of a model train convention in the season 7 episode "Friends of the Road".
